### Version

5.9.0

### Description

During testing, we encountered a trap when wc_InitRng() was called. The trap was triggered by a write to one of the RNG structure fields:
````rng->drbg = NULL;````

The code runs on Infineon TriCore TC29 and TC26 devices, whose architecture only supports word-aligned pointers.
See https://resources.tasking.com/sites/default/files/2021-02/TASKING_Alignment%20Requirements%20Restrictions_WEB.pdf

We examined the memory and saw that the drbg field was not word-aligned.
We fixed this by adding the ````__align(4)```` directive to the WC_RNG struct definition to enforce word alignment. The structure now looks as follows:

```c
/* RNG context */
struct WC_RNG {
    struct OS_Seed seed;
    void* heap;
    byte status;

#if defined(WC_RNG_BANK_SUPPORT) || defined(HAVE_HASHDRBG)

#ifdef HAVE_ANONYMOUS_INLINE_AGGREGATES
    union {
#endif

    #ifdef WC_RNG_BANK_SUPPORT
        struct wc_rng_bank *bankref;
    #endif

    #ifdef HAVE_HASHDRBG
        #ifdef HAVE_ANONYMOUS_INLINE_AGGREGATES
        struct {
        #endif
            /* Hash-based Deterministic Random Bit Generator */
           struct DRBG* drbg;
        #if defined(WOLFSSL_NO_MALLOC) && !defined(WOLFSSL_STATIC_MEMORY)
            struct DRBG_internal drbg_data;
        #endif
        #ifdef WOLFSSL_SMALL_STACK_CACHE
            /* Scratch buffers -- all preallocated by _InitRng(). */
            struct DRBG_internal *drbg_scratch;
            byte *health_check_scratch;

# DTLSHandshake Body Lacks Dynamic CID Message Branches

## Summary

RFC 9147 extends the DTLS 1.3 handshake body selection with two DTLS-specific dynamic Connection ID messages: `request_connection_id` and `new_connection_id`.

wolfSSL implements the ordinary TLS 1.3 / DTLS 1.3 handshake body dispatch path. It parses DTLS handshake headers, passes the body to the TLS 1.3 handshake dispatcher, and handles common message types such as `ClientHello`, `ServerHello`, `CertificateRequest`, `Certificate`, `Finished`, `NewSessionTicket`, and `KeyUpdate`.

The dynamic CID alternatives are not implemented. There is no `request_connection_id(9)` or `new_connection_id(10)` handshake type, no `RequestConnectionId` or `NewConnectionId` body parser/serializer, and no branch in the handshake dispatcher. This confirms ID 028 as **partially satisfied**.

## Standard Requirement

Official standard: <https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9147>

RFC 9147 Section 5.7, `Handshake Protocol`, defines the `DTLSHandshake` body as a selection over `msg_type`:

```text
select (msg_type) {
    case client_hello:          ClientHello;
    case server_hello:          ServerHello;
    case end_of_early_data:     EndOfEarlyData;
    case encrypted_extensions:  EncryptedExtensions;
    case certificate_request:   CertificateRequest;
    case certificate:           Certificate;
    case certificate_verify:    CertificateVerify;
    case finished:              Finished;
    case new_session_ticket:    NewSessionTic

# NewConnectionId cid_spare Usage Is Not Implemented

## Summary

This is a confirmed unsatisfied DTLS 1.3 compliance finding in wolfSSL. RFC 9147 Section 9 defines `NewConnectionId` as a DTLS 1.3 handshake message and defines `usage = cid_spare` as a way to provide spare receiver-selected CIDs. The audited wolfSSL tree supports static CID negotiation and CID bytes in the DTLS 1.3 unified record header, but it does not implement the `NewConnectionId` message or spare-CID state.

## Standard Requirement

Official standard: https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc9147

Local standard text: `document/dtls/RFC9147.txt:2227`

Section: RFC 9147 Section 9, Connection ID Updates

```text
struct {
    ConnectionId cids<0..2^16-1>;
    ConnectionIdUsage usage;
} NewConnectionId;
```

```text
If it is set to "cid_spare", then either an existing or new CID MAY be used.
```

```text
Endpoints SHOULD use receiver-provided CIDs in the order they were provided.
Implementations which receive more spare CIDs than they wish to maintain MAY
simply discard any extra CIDs.
```

The requirement is not just that CID bytes can appear in the record header. A DTLS 1.3 endpoint that receives `NewConnectionId(usage = cid_spare)` needs a parser for the message and state capable of storing or selecting from the receiver-provided spare CIDs.

## Relevant Source Code

`wolfssl-master/wolfssl/internal.h:6057`

```c
typedef struct CIDInfo {
    ConnectionID* tx;
    ConnectionID* rx;
    byte negotiated : 1;
} CIDIn

# mbedTLS Does Not Strictly Enforce the `ServerHello.key_share` Exact Length

## 1. Summary

The issue is about the `key_share` extension in a TLS 1.3 `ServerHello`, specifically the `KeyShareServerHello` structure.

The core mismatch is:

- the TLS 1.3 specification requires `ServerHello.key_share` to contain exactly one `KeyShareEntry`
- mbedTLS server-side construction emits exactly one `KeyShareEntry`
- but mbedTLS client-side parsing accepts extra trailing bytes after that `KeyShareEntry`

So the implementation does not fully enforce the exact structure boundary on the receiving side.

This is the common underlying issue behind the related findings.

## 2. RFC Original Text

The `KeyShareEntry` structure is defined in [RFC 8446, Section 4.2.8](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8446#section-4.2.8):

```text
      struct {
          NamedGroup group;
          opaque key_exchange<1..2^16-1>;
      } KeyShareEntry;
```

For `ServerHello`, the `key_share` extension contains a `KeyShareServerHello` value, defined in [RFC 8446, Section 4.2.8](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8446#section-4.2.8):

```text
      struct {
          KeyShareEntry server_share;
      } KeyShareServerHello;
```

The RFC then states in [RFC 8446, Section 4.2.8](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8446#section-4.2.8):

```text
   server_share:  A single KeyShareEntry value that is in the same group
      as one of the client's shares.
```

And also in [RFC 8446, Section 4.2.8](https://www.rfc-editor.or

[RFC 8446 §4.6.1](https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc8446#section-4.6.1) (NewSessionTicket Message) states:

> Servers MUST NOT use any value greater than 604800 seconds (7 days).

While the OpenSSL **server** correctly caps `ticket_lifetime` at 604800 in `create_ticket_prequel()`, the **client** stores whatever value the server sends without validation.

### Location

`ssl/statem/statem_clnt.c`, in `tls_process_new_session_ticket()` (~line 3170):

```c
if (!PACKET_get_net_4(pkt, &ticket_lifetime_hint)
        ...
s->session->ext.tick_lifetime_hint = ticket_lifetime_hint;
// No check that ticket_lifetime_hint <= 604800 for TLS 1.3
```

The stored value is later used in `ssl/statem/extensions_clnt.c:1389` to decide whether a ticket is still fresh:

```c
if (s->session->ext.tick_lifetime_hint < agesec) {
    /* Ticket is too old. Ignore it. */
    goto dopsksess;
}
```

With `tick_lifetime_hint = 0xFFFFFFFF` (~136 years), this check never triggers.

### Suggested Fix

Add a validation check for TLS 1.3 connections:

```c
if (SSL_CONNECTION_IS_TLS13(s) && ticket_lifetime_hint > 604800) {
    SSLfatal(s, SSL_AD_ILLEGAL_PARAMETER,
             SSL_R_INVALID_TICKET_LIFETIME);
    goto err;
}
```

Or

```c
if (SSL_CONNECTION_IS_TLS13(s) && ticket_lifetime_hint > 604800)
    ticket_lifetime_hint = 604800;
```

### Notes

- The server side already enforces this correctly (`ssl/statem/statem_srvr.c:create_ticket_prequel()`) this is only a client-side validation gap
- TLS 1.2 has

Twelve TLS 1.3 key schedule secrets stored as fixed-size arrays in the `SSL_CONNECTION` struct (ssl/ssl_local.h:1535-1546) are never zeroed via `OPENSSL_cleanse()`. This doesn’t happen after the handshake, on  `SSL_clear()`, or on `SSL_free()`. They persist as cleartext in heap memory until the allocator reuses the pages.

This is inconsistent with how OpenSSL handles similar secrets elsewhere:
  - `SSL_SESSION_free()` cleanses master_key (ssl/ssl_sess.c:856)
  - `tls13_update_key()` cleanses local key/secret (ssl/tls13_enc.c:849)
  - `ext.secure` uses `OPENSSL_secure_clear_free` (ssl/ssl_lib.c:4628)

RFC 8446 §7.1 recommends (SHOULD) erasing intermediate secrets once all derived values are computed.

## Affected Fields

All fields in ssl/ssl_local.h lines 1535-1546, within struct ssl_connection_st:
```
  unsigned char early_secret[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char handshake_secret[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char master_secret[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char resumption_master_secret[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char client_finished_secret[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char server_finished_secret[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char server_finished_hash[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char handshake_traffic_hash[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char client_app_traffic_secret[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char server_app_traffic_secret[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char exporter_master_secret[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
  unsigned char early_exporter_master_secret[EVP_MAX_MD_SIZE];
```
