# OfferedPsks.identities lower-bound inconsistency

## 1. Conclusion

This issue concerns the minimum length constraint on `OfferedPsks.identities`.
RFC 8446 requires `identities<7..2^16-1>`, but the current OpenSSL code path does not enforce a unified hard-fail check for this lower bound. Therefore this item is classified as **Partially Satisfied**.

## 2. RFC 8446 English Source Text

### 2.1 `pre_shared_key` extension structure definition

From [RFC 8446 (TLS 1.3), Section 4.2.11](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8446#section-4.2.11):

```text
The "extension_data" field of this extension contains a
"PreSharedKeyExtension" value:

   struct {
       opaque identity<1..2^16-1>;
       uint32 obfuscated_ticket_age;
   } PskIdentity;

   opaque PskBinderEntry<32..255>;

   struct {
       PskIdentity identities<7..2^16-1>;
       PskBinderEntry binders<33..2^16-1>;
   } OfferedPsks;

   struct {
       select (Handshake.msg_type) {
           case client_hello: OfferedPsks;
           case server_hello: uint16 selected_identity;
       };
   } PreSharedKeyExtension;
```

The key constraint is:

```text
PskIdentity identities<7..2^16-1>;
```

### 2.2 Vector syntax lower-bound meaning

From [RFC 8446, Section 3.4](https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8446#section-3.4):

```text
Variable-length vectors are defined by specifying a subrange of legal
lengths, inclusively, using the notation <floor..ceiling>.
```

The `7` in `<7..2^16-1>` is the inclusive lower bound on the encoded byt

OpenSSL Version
OpenSSL 3.5.0 (and likely all 3.x versions with the new record layer)
Platform
Linux (x86_64), TCP sockets
Description
SSL_write() incorrectly returns a positive value (claiming all bytes were written) when the underlying socket send() system call returns 0 with a non-retryable errno. On a subsequent SSL_write() call, the internal assertion check in tls_write_records() detects leftover pending write buffer data and triggers a fatal error (SSL_R_RECORD_LAYER_FAILURE / ERR_R_SHOULD_NOT_HAVE_BEEN_CALLED).
Root Cause Analysis
The bug is in ssl/record/methods/tls_common.c, function tls_retry_write_records() (around line 1932):
```
i = BIO_write(rl->bio, ..., (unsigned int)TLS_BUFFER_get_left(thiswb));
if (i >= 0) {
    tmpwrit = i;
    if (i == 0 && BIO_should_retry(rl->bio))
        ret = OSSL_RECORD_RETURN_RETRY;
    else
        ret = OSSL_RECORD_RETURN_SUCCESS;  /* <-- BUG */
}
```
When send() returns 0 in sock_write() (crypto/bio/bss_sock.c:139):
1. sock_write() returns 0 and does not set the retry flag (errno is non-retryable)
2. BIO_write() returns 0 (i.e. i = 0)
3. Since i >= 0 is true, the code enters the positive branch
4. i == 0 && BIO_should_retry(rl->bio) is false (no retry flag set)
5. The code falls through to ret = OSSL_RECORD_RETURN_SUCCESS — this is wrong
Then at the buffer consumption check (line 1960):
```
if (i >= 0 && tmpwrit == TLS_BUFFER_get_left(thiswb)) {
    /* tmpwrit=0, but buffer still has data -> FALSE */
} else if (i <= 0) {
    /* i

There is a PKCS#7 padding "bypass" in in `gnutls_cipher_decrypt3()` at `lib/crypto-api.c:535-548`. The validation loop compares each candidate padding byte against `p[*ptext_len - 1]` instead of `p[i]`:

```c
uint8_t padding = p[*ptext_len - 1];
if (!padding || padding > _gnutls_cipher_get_block_size(h->ctx_enc.e))
    return gnutls_assert_val(GNUTLS_E_DECRYPTION_FAILED);

/* Check that the prior bytes are all PADDING */
for (size_t i = *ptext_len - padding; i < *ptext_len; i++) {
    if (padding != p[*ptext_len - 1]) {       /* tautology */
        return gnutls_assert_val(GNUTLS_E_DECRYPTION_FAILED);
    }
}
*ptext_len -= padding;
```

`padding` was initialized from `p[*ptext_len - 1]` three lines earlier, so `padding != p[*ptext_len - 1]` is always false. The loop variable `i` is declared and advanced but never used in the body. The check is a no-op.

Any plaintext ending in a byte L ∈ [1, block_size] is therefore accepted as PKCS#7-padded regardless of what precedes it; the L bytes immediately before the last can be anything. The function returns 0 (success) and reports a `*ptext_len` reduced by L, so the caller receives a plaintext of attacker-chosen length whose tail bytes are not what PKCS#7 requires.

This is reachable from any caller of `gnutls_cipher_decrypt3()` — a public API since 3.7.7 used for CMS / S-MIME / custom protocol decryption. The TLS record layer is unaffected (separate hardened CBC code path).

